ith a strangely blank expression on her face, the lone Shadowknight quite slowly and deliberately ran the Leatherfoot Spy through.  Bloody froth spewed from the hapless halfling’s pain tormented mouth as the broad blade was cruelly turned within him.<br>
<br>
A spout of deepest crimson burst from his chest as the searching steel finally found his aorta and severed it, subsiding quickly as the notched sword was withdrawn and the impending corpse crumpled to the stone floor with an barely audible wheeze.  Kneeling on the chest, the same implement cut through flesh and gristle to sever the head, and the mail clad figure stood somewhat awkwardly staring at it.<br>
<br>
‘Since when did I get so vicious?’,  the victor snarled at the lifeless visage of the vanquished, the laughter of madness in it’s chilling tones.<br>
<br>
She had been wandering, or perhaps more to the point skulking, around the quieter parts of the city of the Teir ‘Dal for weeks.  For so long seldom seen in the city of her birth, the once wanderer now seemed to be nowhere else.  Though always somewhat apart from her kind, the former matron of House D’Fral had previously avoided contact with her peers primarily due to her own insecurity, her lack of self worth.  Now, at the peak of her powers, they avoided her.  <br>
<br>
Though outwardly a normal inhabitant in this city of shadows, from her very essence emanated a darkness that was almost palpable. Behind the glazed look and the still set mouth a rage burned, betrayed visually only by a gleam of darkest fire in the ebon of her eyes – but sensible at an almost visceral level to all who came near her.  <br>
<br>
Her rage was fuelled by the power of the father’s hate, certainly, and by righteous indignation at the failure of her race to assume their rightful place in the world outside.  But more than that, it was fuelled by her own sense of futility, purposelessness, and above all loneliness.  Now given a target, a focus, the rage boiled forth within her.<br>
<br>
Casting the head from her as if in disgust, a scream began deep in the recesses of her mind.  Rising inexorably from within it took over her mind with effortless ease, rising in an uncontrollable crescendo, drowning out all consciousness with its din.  Vomiting forth from her mouth like magma from a volcano the cry burst forth upon the granite walls of the Commons, echoing round it’s passages and caverns, across the pools and falls, silencing all in it’s path.<br>
<br>
As the echoes returned from grot and lake, the sound ceased forth but the scream continued. Like a puppet deprived of it’s strings, Crieth slumped to the floor in a clatter of weapons and armour. Flecks of blood and spittle tarnished the pristine chalcedony of her lips, still formed in the shape of that one single terrible thought:<br>
<br>
‘Why?’<br>
