  <br>
She had first met him when he was but one of the knights of Innoruuk in the Violent Harvest.  He bore the same arms that her old sparring partner, Crieth did - though with considerably better humour - and she had the pleasure of hunting with him on many occasions. On Norrath, Luclin and beyond in the planes of the gods he had led the forces of Hate, and though she fought not in the vanguard of those forces, many a time she had brought forth her healing magics to support his powerful form. <br>
<br>
Though she was sure he despaired of her always irreverent and sometimes downright insolent quips, he was always seemingly laughing with her. He was a fearless leader, having taken her and others many times into the very demesne of the Whore Goddess, and slaughtered all but her and Tunare's most intimate guardians.<br>
<br>
He would also, she thought with a fondness she shared for very few, have made an excellent mate.  <br>
<br>
Though now far removed from the politics of Neriak, Elixar thought how keenly the respected race would feel the loss of the army of the Grange, and it's general of armies. <br>
<br>
Or would they?<br>
<br>
Wryly she admitted to herself that the world cared little about generals and honour these days, and the Children of Neriak were no exception to this sad fact. The priesthood of the spires, herself included, would be as likely to hunt with a paladin of Tunare than hunt them on the hunting groups of Norrath or Luclin.  Even though, deep within, she knew she would miss the Harvest and it's single-mindedness of purpose, a resolution to the fundamental paradox that his retirement represented was no closer to her.<br>
<br>
Why do the gods so singularly choose to take the faithful from this world, leaving the secular masses alone?<br>
<br>
Filing this in her head along with a growing list of numerous other imponderables, Elixar began a murmured incantation to the Dark Father. She would seek for her old friend the caretaker in the city of her birth, and pass on the news - and perhaps share her sadness. In a swirl of argent embers, the Faithstone of Hate coalesced a dimensional gate before her and she stepped forth into it's nothingness. With nought but a brief flash, the gate folded in on itself in a silent implosion, taking stone and wielder with it.<br>
<br>
Elixar B'ladonna<br>
Prophetess of the Spires<br>
